 that which has been buried in the history of time. The contributors look at a wide range of artistic productions, from poetry and fiction, to art, music, and film, and martial arts produced in Cuba, Columbia, Brazil, Haiti, and the United States. Haitian Creole, Spanish, and English are brought together, giving the reader a vivid sense of the multiplicity of voices in the African diaspora. Rather than concentrate on the dispersion of peoples of African descent, this collection focuses instead on the multiple sites of origins in the Americas, as diasporic legacies are found throughout the continent.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 26. Apr 2024) 0aAfrican diaspora. 0aGroup identity. 0aManners and customs. 4aAnthropology and Archaeology : Cultural Anthropology. 4aArea Studies : African Studies. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Black Studies (Global).2bisacsh1 aAbegunde, Osunbimpe, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aAldana, Ligia S., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aAlleyne, Lauren K., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDavid, Ashley, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGarcía-Conde, Luisa, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLara, Ana-Maurine, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMaddox IV, John Thomas, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMartínez, Oilda, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aNathaniel, Daina, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aObi, T. J. Desch, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aPerea, Guesnerth Josué, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aPrater, Tzarina T., econtributor.